ngland"},"en":{"Abt 1270–":"about 1270–Deceased","1235–1309":"1235–1309","1302–1335":"1302–1335","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","Abt 1270":"about 1270","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","devonshire, eng":"Devon, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (north-West Midlands, Lancashire, Yorkshire, and Norfolk): nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, which could be given to someone who wore black and white clothing, had grey-streaked dark hair, or had a loud, chattering voice and impertinent behaviour, or was cunning or sly. The uncomplimentary senses derive from the bird's behavior and are recorded uses of the word in Middle English and early Modern English.","English: occasionally perhaps a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn named <i>Pie</i> ‘magpie’. There were two London taverns so named, but whether these gave rise to a hereditary surname is not known. Surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>pie</i> ‘merciful, compassionate, kind’, a variant of Old French, Anglo-Norman French <i>piu</i>, <i>peu</i>; see   Pew   (2)."],"variants":[{"name":"Pew","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Pugh  .","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>pi(u)</i>, <i>piw</i>, <i>peu</i> ‘holy, pious’, also ‘merciful, kind, compassionate’."]},{"name":"Pyatt","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): nickname either from Middle English <i>piot</i> ‘magpie’ (Old French <i>pïot</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>pie</i>), commonly used to denote a chattering woman, or alternatively from an unrecorded Middle English <i>pyard</i>, an uncomplimentary term derived from the same Old French word + <i>-(h)ard</i>. Compare   Pye  .","Variant of   Piatt  , a surname of French and Walloon origin.","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with the variant <i>Piatt</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]},{"name":"Pie","meanings":["English: variant of   Pye  , in part a cognate of 2 below.","French: nickname from Old French <i>pie</i> ‘magpie’, perhaps given to a talkative person or someone who had a loud, chattering voice.","French (<b>Pié</b>): variant of   Piet   ‘foot’. Compare   Pease   and   Pee  ."]}]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Herbert de Pyn was born about 1270, in Devon, England. She had at least 1 son with Sir. Herbert IV de Pyn Knight."},"et":{"Abt 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1235–1309":"1235–1309","1302–1335":"1302–1335","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","Abt 1270":"umbes 1270","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","devonshire, eng":"Devon, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollut","1235–1309":"1235–1309","1302–1335":"1302–1335","1270–Female":"1270–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","Abt 1270":"noin 1270","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","devonshire, eng":"Devon, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1270–":"environ 1270–Décédée","1235–1309":"1235–1309","1302–1335":"1302–1335","1270–Female":"1270–Décédée","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","Abt 1270":"environ 1270","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","devonshire, eng":"Devon, Angleterre","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs Herbert de Pyn est née environ 1270, à Devon, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Sir. Herbert IV de Pyn Knight."},"de":{"Abt 1270–":"um 1270–Verstorben","1235–1309":"1235–1309","1302–1335":"1302–1335","1270–Female":"1270–Verstorben","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","Abt 1270":"um 1270","1309":"1309","1270":"1270","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","devonshire, eng":"Devon, England","Upton Pyne, Devon, England":"Upton Pyne, Devon, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs Herbert de Pyn wurde um 1270 in Devon, England geboren. Sie hatte mit Sir. Herbert IV de Pyn Knight mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"Abt 1270–":"about 1270–Desede","123